\description{
Refits a \code{grf::causal_forest()} after replacing the conditional outcome
\verb{m(x) = E[Y | X = x]} and propensity \verb{e(x) = E[W | X = x]} with the
best-performing nuisance estimator from a candidate pool, scored by
shared K-fold cross-fit weighted CV loss. The CATE estimator and
identification assumptions of \code{grf} are unchanged --- only the
Robinson-residualisation nuisances are swapped (and only if the winner
beats grf's own baseline by a configurable margin).
}
\details{
\strong{What this function is for.} A diagnostic + drop-in replacement.
grf's default nuisance estimators (regression forests on Y and W) are
usually fine but not always best. \code{autocf()} runs a small candidate
pool under a shared K-fold cross-fit protocol with weighted CV loss
(mean-squared error for Y and continuous W; Brier score for binary
W, which is identical to MSE on 0/1 outcomes), reports the comparison
table, and only swaps in a competitor if it beats the grf baseline by
a margin you choose.

\strong{grf baseline scored out-of-bag.} The "grf" candidate is scored on
the fitted forest's own out-of-bag honest nuisances
(\code{c.forest$Y.hat} / \code{c.forest$W.hat}) --- the predictions you actually
keep --- rather than refit per fold. Every other candidate is still
scored on strict K-fold OOF predictions. Per-fold weighted MSE for the
grf baseline is computed by binning its OOB residuals into the same K
folds, so the 1-SE comparison machinery is unchanged.

\strong{1-SE rule for the swap.} With finite-sample CV
noise any non-trivial candidate will produce some random improvement
on a particular seed. Default \code{min_improvement = "1se"} requires the
mean fold-wise loss reduction to exceed the paired-fold standard
error of that reduction:
\deqn{\text{swap} \iff
  \bar d_K - \widehat{SE}(\bar d_K) > 0,
  \quad d_k = \text{loss}^{\text{grf}}_k - \text{loss}^{\text{cand}}_k.}
This is the same kind of conservativism that \code{glmnet}'s \code{lambda.1se}
uses, generalized to model selection. Use \code{min_improvement = "0"} to
force any improvement to fire, or supply a numeric absolute threshold.

\strong{Weighted CV losses.} When
\code{c.forest$sample.weights} is non-trivial, both training and per-fold
loss computation are weighted, so the loss being minimised matches
how the chosen nuisances will actually be used downstream by grf.
Candidates that cannot accept training weights (currently \code{tabpfn})
are dropped from the pool with a warning when weights are
non-trivial.

\strong{Selection-induced inference.} Picking the best of M candidates by
CV loss is a model-selection step. It is benign here because
\code{grf::causal_forest()} uses a Neyman-orthogonal R-learner score for
the second stage; small perturbations in the chosen nuisance do not
invalidate sqrt(n) inference (Chernozhukov et al., 2018; Foster &
Syrgkanis, 2019). Without orthogonality this would not be safe.

\strong{Convergence-rate caveat.} CV-loss minimization picks the lowest
finite-sample loss, not the best convergence rate. For valid sqrt(n)
downstream inference (e.g. \code{grf::average_treatment_effect()}),
chosen nuisances must converge at \code{o(n^{-1/4})}. The default pool
members (grf reg-forest, glmnet under sparsity, xgboost under
boosting consistency, BART under Rockova & van der Pas, 2020) are
believed adequate at typical n; tabpfn has no formal rate proof and
should be treated as exploratory when downstream confidence intervals
matter.

\strong{Reproducibility under \code{future} plans.} xgboost's mlr3 AutoTuner
inner CV runs through the \code{future} framework. To prevent
non-deterministic seeding under user-set \code{future::plan(multisession)}
or similar, \code{autocf()} forces \code{future::plan("sequential")} for the
duration of its call and restores the previous plan on exit.
}
